        title: "Case File Architecture",
        content: "A well-structured case file has distinct sections that allow rapid navigation during prep and rounds.\n\n**Section 1: The Constructive Case.** This is your core position — the arguments you will present in your constructive speeches. It should include your framework, contentions, evidence, and impact analysis. Have multiple versions: a full version for unlimited prep and a condensed version you can deliver within time constraints.\n\n**Section 2: Blocks.** Blocks are pre-written responses to specific arguments you expect to encounter. Name each block clearly: 'Block: Economic Growth DA,' 'Block: Federalism Counterplan,' 'Block: Util Framework.' Each block should contain your best 3-5 responses with supporting evidence.\n\n**Section 3: Evidence Index.** A master list of all your evidence, organized by topic and tagged with source quality ratings. This lets you find specific cards quickly when you need them during a round.\n\n**Section 4: Strategy Notes.** Notes on how to approach different types of opponents, judge adaptations, and strategic decisions you have made. Include post-round reflections: what worked, what did not, and what you want to change.",
