        content: "Blocks are the backbone of your case file. A great block transforms a potentially devastating opponent argument into a manageable challenge you can handle confidently.\n\n**Block Structure:** Each block should follow this format:\n\n1. **Label:** A clear, descriptive name (e.g., 'AT: Spending Disadvantage' where 'AT' means 'Answering Their')\n2. **Overview:** A 2-3 sentence summary of your overall response strategy\n3. **Responses:** Numbered points, each containing a claim, warrant, and evidence card if applicable\n4. **Cross-Application Notes:** References to other arguments in your case that can help answer this position\n\n**Prioritize Your Responses:** Put your strongest answer first. In a fast-paced round, you may not have time to read every response in the block. If you only get through the first two points, those should be your most devastating answers.\n\n**Multiple Levels of Response:** The best blocks attack at multiple levels. Include responses that challenge the argument's logic, its evidence, its link to the topic, and its impact. Even if your opponent can defend against one type of attack, they are unlikely to survive all four.\n\n**Breadth vs. Depth:** For common arguments you expect to face frequently, build deep blocks with 5-7 responses. For less common arguments, 2-3 targeted responses may suffice. Allocate your preparation time based on how likely you are to face each argument.",
