        content: "The evidence in your case file needs to be more than a collection of quotes. It needs to be strategically integrated with your arguments.\n\n**Tagging Evidence:** Every evidence card should have a 'tag' — a one-sentence summary that captures the card's key claim. The tag should be arguable on its own, so if a judge only hears the tag and not the full card, they still understand your argument. Bad tag: 'Healthcare spending.' Good tag: 'Universal coverage reduces total healthcare spending by 15% through administrative efficiency.'\n\n**Highlighting Key Passages:** In longer evidence cards, bold or highlight the most important sentences. During a round, you may need to quickly identify the critical language rather than reading the entire card.\n\n**Source Documentation:** For every card, record the complete citation: author, title, publication, date, and page number. Incomplete citations undermine your credibility with evidence-focused judges and can result in penalties in some formats.\n\n**Evidence Pairing:** Group evidence that works together. If you have a card establishing a problem and another showing your policy solves it, keep them together. If you have a card on economic impact and another quantifying that impact, link them. This pairing speeds up your argument construction during prep time.",
