        title: "Structuring Rights-Based Arguments",
        content: "Effective rights-based arguments in debate require careful construction to avoid sounding like mere assertions.\n\n**Step 1: Identify the Right.** Name the specific right at stake and classify it (negative/positive, natural/legal, individual/group). Precision matters: 'the right to freedom of expression' is better than 'freedom.'\n\n**Step 2: Ground the Right.** Explain why this right exists using one or more of the justificatory traditions. A rights claim without philosophical grounding is just an assertion.\n\n**Step 3: Show the Violation.** Demonstrate exactly how the policy or action in question violates (or would violate) this right. Be specific about the mechanism of violation. 'This surveillance program violates privacy rights by collecting personal communications without consent or judicial oversight.'\n\n**Step 4: Argue the Priority.** Explain why this right should take priority over competing considerations. Rights are meant to trump other concerns, but you may need to explain why. Is this a fundamental right? Is it constitutionally protected? Does violating it set a dangerous precedent?\n\n**Step 5: Address Limitations.** Acknowledge that most rights are not absolute. Even the right to free speech does not protect incitement to violence. By proactively addressing limitations, you demonstrate sophistication and make your argument harder to attack.",
