        content: "Some of the most challenging and interesting debates arise when rights conflict with each other.\n\n**Common Conflicts:** Freedom of speech vs. protection from hate speech. Religious liberty vs. anti-discrimination protections. Privacy vs. public safety. Property rights vs. environmental protection. Individual autonomy vs. collective welfare.\n\n**Resolution Strategies:**\n\n**Hierarchy of Rights:** Argue that some rights are more fundamental than others. Life and physical security are often placed above property or economic rights. This does not eliminate the lesser right but establishes priority when they conflict.\n\n**Proportionality Analysis:** Argue that any limitation on a right must be proportional to the interest it serves. A minor limitation on privacy for a major security benefit may be justified, but a massive invasion of privacy for a marginal security improvement is not.\n\n**Scope Limitation:** Argue that one of the conflicting rights does not actually apply as broadly as claimed. 'Freedom of speech does not extend to direct incitement because incitement falls outside the purpose for which the right was established.'\n\n**Balancing Test:** Propose a specific framework for weighing the competing rights in this particular case. 'We should protect whichever right, if violated, causes more severe and irreversible harm.' This gives the judge a principled basis for resolving the conflict.",
