        content: "At the Master level, you should be able to deploy several advanced rights-based techniques.\n\n**The Slippery Slope Defense:** 'If we allow this minor rights violation today, we establish a precedent that will justify greater violations tomorrow.' This argument is powerful when you can show historical examples of rights erosion following initial concessions. Be careful to provide evidence rather than mere speculation.\n\n**The Structural Argument:** 'Rights exist not just to protect individuals but to maintain the structure of democratic governance. When the government violates privacy rights, it does not just harm those surveilled — it changes the relationship between citizen and state in ways that threaten democracy itself.'\n\n**The Intersectionality Argument:** 'Rights violations rarely affect everyone equally. This policy disproportionately impacts marginalized communities who have historically been the targets of government overreach.' This connects rights arguments to equity and justice concerns.\n\n**The International Norms Argument:** 'This policy violates not just domestic law but international human rights standards that represent a global consensus about fundamental protections.' Invoking international norms adds authority and breadth to your rights claim.\n\n**The Chilling Effect:** 'Even if this policy does not directly violate rights, the fear it creates will deter people from exercising their rights. The chilling effect on free speech, association, and political participation is itself a rights violation.'",
