        content: "In competitive debate, 'cutting cards' refers to the process of preparing evidence for use in rounds. The term comes from the days when debaters literally cut passages from printed articles and pasted them onto index cards. Today the process is digital, but the name persists.\n\nCutting cards is both an art and a science. A well-cut card delivers maximum persuasive impact in minimum reading time. A poorly cut card buries the key claim in irrelevant text, misrepresents the source, or lacks the context needed to be convincing.\n\nThis lesson teaches you the Master-level techniques for evidence preparation: selecting passages, formatting cards, ensuring accuracy, and building an evidence base that gives you a decisive advantage in every round. These skills are essential in policy and Lincoln-Douglas debate, but the principles of evidence preparation apply to every format.",
