        title: "Card Formatting Standards",
        content: "Proper card formatting makes your evidence accessible, credible, and efficient to use in rounds.\n\n**The Citation Line.** Every card begins with a complete citation. The standard format includes: Author last name, first name; year of publication; title of article or book; name of publication or publisher. For online sources, include the URL. For academic papers, include volume and page numbers. A complete citation signals professionalism and allows judges and opponents to verify your evidence.\n\n**The Tag Line.** After the citation, write a one-sentence tag that captures the card's key argument. This is the claim you are making with this evidence. The tag should be arguable on its own — if the judge hears nothing else, the tag communicates your point. Write tags in active voice with clear subjects and verbs.\n\n**The Card Body.** The actual evidence passage follows the tag. Bold or underline the key sentences — the phrases that directly support your tag. In many debate formats, you will read only the highlighted portions during your speech and make the full text available for inspection.\n\n**Highlighting Discipline.** Do not highlight too much or too little. Too much highlighting defeats the purpose — judges and opponents cannot identify your key claims. Too little means you are relying on a small fragment that may lack context. Aim to highlight the sentences that directly support your tag while leaving context visible in unhighlighted text.",
