        title: "Common Card-Cutting Mistakes",
        content: "Even experienced debaters make errors in evidence preparation. Awareness of these mistakes helps you avoid them.\n\n**Power-Tagging:** Writing a tag that overstates what the evidence actually says. If your card says 'costs may increase moderately,' do not tag it 'costs will skyrocket.' Power-tagging destroys credibility when opponents read the full card and expose the mismatch.\n\n**Straw-Clipping:** Removing words from the middle of a quoted passage to change its meaning. This is considered an ethical violation in competitive debate. If you need to omit text for length, use ellipses and ensure the remaining text accurately represents the author's argument.\n\n**Source Laundering:** Citing a secondary source as if it were the primary source. If a news article quotes a study, cite the original study, not the article. If you cannot access the original, acknowledge that you are citing through a secondary source.\n\n**Date Neglect:** Using outdated evidence without acknowledging its age. A 2015 statistic about social media usage is essentially useless in a 2026 debate. If older evidence is genuinely relevant (for historical context or foundational theory), acknowledge the date and explain why it still matters.\n\n**Context Stripping:** Cutting a passage that presents a hypothetical, conditional, or opposing argument as if it were the author's own position. Always read enough of the surrounding text to understand whether the author is endorsing, questioning, or refuting the claim you are cutting.",
