        content: "Individual cards are building blocks. Your goal is to construct an integrated evidence base that supports your entire case architecture.\n\n**Coverage Mapping:** After cutting cards on a topic, map your evidence against your case outline. Where do you have strong evidentiary support? Where are the gaps? Gaps in your evidence base are vulnerabilities your opponents will exploit.\n\n**Depth and Redundancy:** For your most critical arguments, have multiple cards from independent sources. If your entire solvency argument rests on a single card, a successful evidence challenge could collapse your case. Three cards from different authors making the same point provides resilience.\n\n**Offensive and Defensive Evidence:** Do not only cut evidence supporting your position. Cut evidence that directly refutes the strongest opposing arguments. Defensive evidence that says 'the claimed harm does not actually occur' or 'the proposed mechanism fails because...' is just as valuable as offensive evidence supporting your case.\n\n**Quality over Quantity:** Twenty carefully selected, well-formatted cards are more useful than a hundred hastily cut ones. Each card should earn its place in your file by being specific, well-sourced, and clearly tagged. Remove cards that are redundant, outdated, or vague.",
