        content: "At the Master level, you need to cut cards efficiently without sacrificing quality. Here are techniques to speed up the process.\n\n**Template Usage:** Create a standard template for your cards with pre-formatted sections for citation, tag, and body. Paste new evidence into the template rather than formatting from scratch each time. This simple step can cut your formatting time in half.\n\n**Batch Processing:** Instead of cutting one card at a time from start to finish, batch similar tasks. Read through all your sources first and mark relevant passages. Then write all your tags. Then format all your cards. Batching similar cognitive tasks is more efficient than constantly switching between reading, evaluating, and formatting.\n\n**Collaborative Cutting:** Divide research responsibilities among team members. One person researches economic impacts while another handles security arguments. Share results in a standardized format so everyone benefits from the full team's research output.\n\n**Digital Tools:** Use keyboard shortcuts, text expansion tools, and citation managers to automate repetitive tasks. A citation manager like Zotero can auto-generate formatted citations from a DOI or URL. Text expansion can insert your standard card template with a single keystroke.\n\n**Quality Checkpoints:** After cutting a batch of cards, do a quality review. Read each tag against the highlighted evidence. Does the tag accurately reflect the card? Is the citation complete? Is the highlighting focused? Catching errors during review is far less costly than discovering them mid-round.",
